Xmltv type definition has been extended to support Android TV
Input Framework and static video contents. Previous xmltv.dtd
misses the type definition of those extended fields, thus android
studio xml validation lint errors still exist. By completing the
type definition, the number of validation errors has been reduced
to 0.

rich_tv_input_xmltv_feed.xml is updated to match the ordering
of child elements defined in xmltv.dtd.

msg:
Squashed commit of the following:

commit 897a1d1b5e70ed1c426375827e5ca62fbc349dc5
Author: Alice Ching <aliceching@google.com>
Date:   Fri Apr 17 13:59:11 2015 -0700

    Update the GitHub urls.

commit a147a60e693eade95de8b5c26f407cf75c694483
Author: Alice Ching <aliceching@google.com>
Date:   Tue Apr 14 11:44:15 2015 -0700

    Move the broadcast unregister to before we unbind the service.

    This is to prevent a race condition where MainActivity is paused and saved
    before the onServiceDisconnected call is made.

commit 14fecb5d1950a9485e5c163e268648771c97c75a
Author: Alice Ching <aliceching@google.com>
Date:   Fri Apr 10 16:33:57 2015 -0700

    Register/unregister broadcast intents with service bind/unbind.

    Seems like there would be a race condition when the app is started for the first
    time, where intents are registered before the service exists.

msg: Merge "Hackathon Cleanup"

Clean up RegistrationIntentService and MyInstanceIDListenerService

- Consolidate duplicate code between the two classes.
- Make it more explicit where to hook in third-party server calls.
- Minimize number of I/O operations, only writing to SharedPrefs when needed.
- Swap calls to SharedPreferences.commit() with apply().
- Added TODO to add INSTANCE_ID_SCOPE, when it's ready.

Change-Id: I5aa80b57a04f9702b680fba77b41bda115a9e8f8

Simplify GCM Quickstart experience using PubSub

Adds option to use PubSub to address GCM Quickstart client, avoiding
the need to copy/paste a registration ID from logcat.

Clients subscribe to the "/topics/global" topic. The GcmSender CLI app
will use this topic if no registration ID is supplied.

msg:
Re-organize the policies layout of TestDPC app

Divide the policies into 3 categories:
1. Device owner only policy
   The options are inflated in PolicyManagementFragment but disabled
   when the app is running in a managed profile.
2. Device owner / profile owner policy
   The options are inflated in PolicyManagementFragment.
3. Profile owner specific policies
   The options are inflated in ProfilePolicyManagementFragment.

If testDPC app is a device owner, the policy management fragment is shown
when it is launched from the primary profile.

msg:
Sort apps alphabetically

Changes:
- The sort order of the following lists are changed, they are sorted by the name that is displayed.
  - the list of apps in "Enable system apps"
  - the dropdown list of apps in "Manage app restrictions"
  - the list of apps in "Manage lock task list"
  - the list of apps in "Block uninstallation list"
  - the list of input methods in "Set input methods"
  - the list of services in "Set accessibility services"
  - the list of account types in "Get account type with management disabled"
- The below lists display the service name instead of the application name.
  To achieve this, ToggleComponentsArrayAdapter no longer get the display name on its own,
  it now get the name from the subclass through getDisplayName().
  - the list of apps in "Manage lock task list"
  - the list of input methods in "Set input methods"
  - the list of services in "Set accessibility services"

- the list of apps in "Enable system apps"
- the dropdown list of apps in "Manage app restrictions"
- the list of apps in "Manage lock task list"
- the list of apps in "Block uninstallation list"
- the list of input methods in "Set input methods"
- the list of services in "Set accessibility services"
- the list of account types in "Get account type with management disabled"
  note: some dummy account types were added before the test by pressing "Toggle account management"

the actual string values of restrictions. This approach is error

Bug: 24291861
Change-Id: I36fd752ba28513cb952c7b923b088d612aa224a1

Hide the actionbar in Fragment onResume.

When the device is going through setup screens, there
should not be an actionbar. Currently, we are achieving this
by hiding the actionbar before the fragment starts but when
the activity is re-created, we are not hiding the actionbar.
Instead, handle hiding the actionbar in Fragment itself.

Since TestDPC is not expected to run on pre-L, platformRelease
will work just fine.

Remove user restrictions in Manage work profile specific policy section.

Currently, we have ALLOW_PARENT_PROFILE_APP_LINKING and
DISALLOW_CROSS_PROFILE_COPY_PASTE in two places: under "Manage work
profile specific policy section" and under "Set user restrictions".
So, removing it from one of them.

Refactor app restriction fragment

b/28012233.

   in different key value pair setting. So the caller start the dialog
   and receives the result in onActivityResult.
2. The dialog handles bundle and bundle array type as well, so no more
   special handling is needed in caller side.
3. Rewrite StringArrayTypeInputAdapter to avoid passing the adapter around.

Also fixed two bugs:
1. Show add button outside of list
2. Fix setting bundle array in app restriction

Change-Id: Id63ab7d65f8f90d6e66653b58e94c17ccaaf1ba0

Add search functionality to testdpc

We have crawler to skim through all preference xmls of indexable
fragments and then we saved the index to a FTS table in sqlite database.
All searchable fragments extends a base class that except preference key
as argument, so that they will scroll down the target preference and
highlight it. Also, all searchable preference must implements isAvailable
in order to determine whether it should be shown in the search result page.

1. PreferenceCrawler is the crawler to skims through the XML
2. PolicySearchFragment process the search query and show the search result.
3. PreferenceIndexSqliteOpenHelper handles all sqlite operations

To add a new searachable fragment, you only need to
1. Make sure your fragment extends BaseSearchablePolicyPreferenceFragment
2. Register your fragments in IndexableFragments
And then you are good to go!

PS: the preference-v14 library is now broken, it is fixed in the internal
repo though. This commit should be merged only when the fix is in the
public build.

Fix isManagedProfileOwner() before profile is enabled.

Previously, we check the app is the profile owner and that there is more
than one profile to make sure it is a managed profile. However, before
the managed profile is enabled it does not count as a profile so the
test was giving incorrect results. Now, we assume it is a managed
profile if the app is a profile owner as TestDPC only supports being a
profile owner in a managed profile.

This only affects pre-M devices as N introduces DPM.isManagedProfile().

* changes:
  Fix bugs in KioskModeActivity.
  Implement setLockTaskFeatures().

Implement ActivityOptions.setLockTaskMode().

In P, we introduce a way to launch a new task directly into LockTask
mode: ActivityOptions.setLockTaskMode(). This differs from previous
methods in that no special code is required in the target activity
itself (e.g. calling Activity.startLockTask() or setting the
lockTaskMode manifest attribute).

In this change, we implement this new API. Specifically, a new option is
added in PolicyManagementFragment to relaunch this activity with the
above ActivityOptions. This new option is put in parallel with the
existing "Start lock task mode" option.

(cherry picked from commit 722e260b83a5719961f5dea19d06972206494a4b)

TestDPC: Add key generation and testing facilities

Add activities to exercise the new code in the DevicePolicyManager for
generating keys directly in Keystore and key access control mechanism.
In particular:
- Key installation now asks if the key should be user-selectable.
- New preference for generating a key via the DevicePolicyManager (the
  key can also be set to be user-selectable).
- New preference for exercising a key: Asking the user to choose a key
  alias, then performing a signing operation using the private key
  associated with this alias and a validation operations with the
  public key from the certificate associated with this alias.

For these changes:
- A new dependency on BouncyCastle PKIX package has been introduced.
- The CertificateUtils class has been imported from cts. It cannot be
  extracted to a common library since the code here uses the public copy
  of BouncyCastle, with different package names.
- A new checkbox has been added to the dialog for choosing alias name.

Follow-up work may include additional check-boxes at key generation time
for requesting attestation record and inclusion of device identifiers.

* DELEGATION_CERT_SELECTION
* DELEGATION_PACKAGE_INSTALLATION

DO, grant delegation to TestDPC replica, and exercise the delegated
capabilities from TestDPC replica.

msg:
Replace setAutoTimeRequired and getAutoTimeRequired with setAutoTime and getAutoTime

* In DPM, setAutoTimeRequired and getAutoTimeRequired must be called either by
  the device owner or the profile owner (since Android 8). This CL allows TestDPC
  to call this method on the profile owner and not just the device owner.
* This CL also adds a preference to call setAutoTime and getAutoTime.
* There will be a follow-up CL to enforce setAutoTime and getAutoTime is only called
  by the device owner, profile owner of the primary user  or profile owner of an
  organization owned device.

  networks that have been configured by the device owner.

  user from modifying networks as well as the device owner.
* This CL updates TestDPC to allow a COPE profile owner to modify the preference
  that sets whether modification of configured networks is allowed. This CL
  also updates this preference to call the new API.

msg:
Added Shell command to set the user icons.

The icons must be located under the user's sdcard/Pictures/UserIcons
directory; notice that starting on Android R, Shell cannot access
other user's data, so this CL also added a ContentProvider that can
be used to manage this files. For example, to set the icon for a
managed user with id 10, you'd need to run 2 commands:

$ adb shell content write --user 10 --uri content://com.afwsamples.testdpc.usericoncontentprovider/icon.png < ~/tmp/icon.png
$ adb shell dumpsys activity service --user 10 com.afwsamples.testdpc set-user-icon icon.png

msg:
TestDPC disable IME on the personal profile

Background:
* On organization-owned devices with managed profiles,
  the work admin needs to be able to restrict
  IMEs on the personal side.
* They should be able to restrict IMEs without having
  visibility on the personal side. This is done by
  introducing the ability for the admin to set the
  permitted IMEs on the parent profile.

Changes:
* Add new preference to modify permitted input methods
  on the parent profile

Manual test steps:
* Set up organization-owned device and download
  IME apps on the personal profile
* Download TestDPC
* Select prefence Set input methods on parent
* Select allow only system IMEs and check Settings to see
  all non-system IMEs are disabled.
* Select allow all IME apps and check Settings to see
  no IME apps are disabled.

Add support for security logging delegation

Test: The following manual steps:
  # Install both TestDPC and the Replica version of TestDPC
  # Set as device owner
  adb shell dpm set-device-owner com.afwsamples.testdpc/.DeviceAdminReceiver
  # Reboot the device so the device owner change take effect
  adb reboot
  # Launch TestDPC, enable security logging
  # Generate a security log event, force it to be pushed out
  adb shell whoami
  adb shell dpm force-security-logs
  # Find log in TestDPC, Device Owner Management > Request Security Logs
  # Launch TestDPC-Replica
  # Observe that security logging is not viewable from TestDPC-Replica
  # Observe that no delegations are given to TestDPC-Replica, e.g.
  #   it's not mentioned at the top of the app
  # Launch TestDPC, give Security Logging Delegation to TestDPC-Replica:
  #   Delegation > Generic Delegation > Access security logging
  # Launch TestDPC-Replica, observe at top of app:
  #   "app has delegated permissions"
  # Observe that TestDPC-Replica has access to security logging settings
  #   under Device Owner Management
  # Generate a security log event, force it to be pushed out
  adb shell whoami
  adb shell dpm force-security-logs
  # Find log in TestDPC-Replica, Device Owner Management > Request Security Logs
  # Launch TestDPC, take away Security Logging Delegation from TestDPC-Replica
  #   Delegation > Generic Delegation > Access security logging
  # Observe that security logging is not viewable from TestDPC-Replica
  # Observe that no delegations are given to TestDPC-Replica, e.g.
  #   it's not mentioned at the top of the app

added onMissing handling

Adding handling of the onMissing event allows the graphic trackers to
hide a temporarily missing item from view, which can happen occasionally
during tracking.  This can reduce the perception of "lag", since it
won't show a stale detection on screen when the detection hasn't really
occurred.

msg:
open sourcing CameraSource

Please read over this carefully, including the comments.  This class will
be released to third party developers.

The reason for open sourcing this class is that third party developers
want more customization than this class is capable of exposing (e.g.,
support for torch mode, selecting a specific resolution, etc.).  Part
of the difficulty was that this class uses camera1 under the hood, but
we don't want to expose any details of camera1 in the API because it
is deprecated.  Another difficulty is that some developers want to use
features that aren't backward compatible, but we don't want to have
such features in the official API.  Open sourcing this class will give
developers the flexibility to customize this however it best suits
their particular app.

This class doesn't include any trade secrets, vision related or
otherwise.  But it is fairly detailed and hairy.

Change-Id: Ib2e0b0d2d3d0526b20783051718c9f48cfca50af

Adding Barcode reader sample with CameraSource.java

This sample starts with the open source version of CameraSource.java, and
then adds a main activity that demonstrates how to pass data between two
activities.  It also shows how to use the CameraSource to control parameters
such as focus, flash, and zoom.

The first revision of this checkin is the original CameraSource.java, then
the subsequent ones are the one ultimately used in the sample.

created "googly eyes" demo app

This is the code for an app that I will demonstrate at Google I/O.
It tracks eye landmarks and state in real time, overlaying a googly
eyes animation over the eyes as fast as possible.  It can be used
in either front facing or rear facing modes.  Each mode is optimized
differently -- front facing tracks a single large face (faster) and
rear facing mode will track multiple, smaller faces (slower).

Update to lint from Studio 4.1 canary 2

This includes lint checks for lint checks!

Merge pull request #25 from tnorbye/studio41

Update to lint from Studio 4.1 canary 2

Cleanup: Flatten directory structure, update to new versions

This sample project had multiple subfolders, for Android Studio 2,
Android Studio 3, and Android Studio 4. Most of this was obsolete.  This
is now flattened into just one sample, which shows how to write a lint
check for a recent version of Studio/AGP.

It also updates the lint checks in various ways: using JUnit4 for the
unit test instead of JUnit3, providing a Vendor registration for the
issue registry, updating various versions of plugins and libraries to
the latest versions, etc etc.

Added the concept of source AARs (srcaar).

Unity will happily attempt to process all AARs included in a project
which is unfortunate since some AARs need to be expanded and have
variable replacement applied.  This change allows AARs to be included
in a project using the .srcaar extension which the Jar Resolver will
treat as typical AAR files, copying / expanding them as required.

Fixed incorrect update of unpacked AARs.

e.g foo-1.2.3.aar would be unpacked as foo-1.2.3 and end up
being parsed as package foo-1.2 such that when checking for
updates of foo, version 1.2.3 would look like a new version vs.

Committing automated building of packages

Moved Jar Resolver into a single DLL and added version manager.

In addition:
* Adds a project for the Jar Resolver plug-in.  After copying the unity
  DLLs into the project directory the plug-in DLL can be built with
  monodevelop.
* Updates the build script with rules to build the single plug-in DLL.
* Removed dependency upon tests when building the plug-in.  Tests are
  still built and run by the prebuild rule.
* Renamed plug-in DLL in the Gradle build script to encode the Jar Resolver
  version and targets (i.e metadata).
* Changed default metadata of the Jar Resolver to be disabled in all
  Unity environments.
* Made all platform specific conditional at runtime (rather than using
  conditional compilation).  This is required as everything is now baked
  into a single DLL.
* Added a version manager component which disables old plug-ins, enables
  the latest revisions and manages file deletions when new .unitypackage files
  are imported if they embed a manifest file.

msg:
Fixed Jar Resolver auto-resolution.

There were some cases where auto-resolution wouldn't happen correctly
now the Version Handler is part of the plug-in and plays with asset
metadata on load.  So this change simplifies auto-resolution to only
prevent re-entrant auto-resolution and also initializes the app bundle
ID on load so that an auto-resolution doesn't occur the first time
the bundle ID is polled.

Also:
* Fixed stale bundle ID used to perform resolution when it's changed.
* Restored version handling of the plugin's manifest.

msg:
Fixed Play Services Resolver being disabled on import at the same version.

When Unity imports a package with the same GUIDs it will apply the metadata
from the newly imported package into the project.  In the case of the
Play Services Resolver, by default IOSResolver and JarResolver are disabled
forcing the user to manually re-enable the DLLs as the VersionResolver
will not see metadata usually encoded in the filename
(plugin_v1.2.3_tEditor.dll will have been renamed plugin.dll) instructing
it to enable the plugins.

This patch moves the target platform to labels of each component such that
an import will force the VersionHandler to re-enable the components when it
executes.

In addition, this adds the version number of each component into the file
metadata so that it isn't lost when imported over an existing plugin at the
same revision.

msg: Merging bug fixes.

Fixed VersionHandler and IOSResolver compatibility with Unity 4.

Unity 4 doesn't have the UnityEngine.PluginImporter class and
stores the Xcode DLL in a yet another location.

Since the PluginImporter is not available in Unity 4,
VersionHandler targetting is disabled as it's not possible
- without hacking .meta files - to enable / disable targeting
for plugins (DLLs).

As the Mono distribution is slightly different, the IOSResolver
has been modified to only call methods that use the Xcode
plugin in separate methods after the workaround for loading
the plugin has been installed.  In addition, since the Xcode DLL
seemingly moves with each Unity OSX release, a brute force file
search is now used to search for the Xcode DLL if it isn't in
the default location.

msg:
Fixed IOSResolver to handle PlayerSettings.iOS.targetOSVersionString

PlayerSettings.iOS.targetOSVersionString now specifies the target iOS
SDK.  This is problematic as the new string is freeform and can
therefore result in users providing an invalid version which can cause
builds to fail.  In the case of the IOSResolver plugin it was causing
an exception when trying to convert the string to an integer
representation.  This patch applies the following:

* Uses reflection to choose between targetOSVersionString and
  targetOSVersion (enum) methods of reading / writing the target SDK
  verion.
* Provides validation of the version string when converting to an
  integer representation.
* Handles invalid conversions (though that shouldn't happen if the
  validation is correct).
* Provides a fallback / default version when the provided SDK string
  can't be parsed.

Change-Id: I8f5ba0a72a95a6ccd9aae487f956c56a5e06028f

Added support for shared libraries in AARs.

AAR support in Unity varies by version and build system, this patch
adds support for shared libraries (.so) files in AARs using a variety
of methods:
* Unity 4:
  - Internal (default) build system
    Shared libraries in the jni folder of AARs are supported but the
    "jni" folder is ignored when AARs are expanded / exploded so this
    copies shared libraries to the "lib" folder in the expanded AAR
    where they're included in the built APK.
* Unity <= 5.4
  - Internal (default) build system
    Similar behavior as Unity 4 except only AARs with shared libs or
	that require variable expansion are exploded.
* Unity 5.5
  - Internal (default) build system
    Same behavior as Unity 5.4
  - Gradle / Android Studio
    Settings dialog can disable expansion / explosion of AARs as
	they're supported natively by the Android Gradle build system.
	The settings dialog is required to configure this behavior as
	Unity does not set the applicationId variable in the generated
	build.gradle.

In addition:
* Enabled the Android Resolver settings dialog when any platform is
  selected.
* Made it possible to configure the target folder for AARs / exploded
  AAR directories.  Though this turned up a bug in Unity's Android
  library search process which fails to find libraries in subdirectories
  so the functionality is disabled at the moment.

https://github.com/googlesamples/unity-jar-resolver/issues/34
https://github.com/googlesamples/unity-jar-resolver/issues/29

msg:
Handle empty string returned by Unity for "targetOSVersionString"
property.

New projects in Unity can sometimes return an empty string for the
iOS targetOSVersionString property. Toggling the value within Unity
build settings will resolve this issue. If not toggled, podfiles will
be created with '' as the target sdk and pod install commands will fail
as the minimum target criteria of pods will not be met. Checking for both
and empty string will default to using DEFAULT_TARGET_SDK in this
scenario.

Change-Id: I4c618e9b04c9e671247ffaa42be6017200e4e670
fixed typo in build script for nunit console location

Fixed explosion of AARs when the bundle ID is modified.

When AARs are exploded the bundle ID is injected into the exploded files.
If the bundle ID is changed the exploded AAR should be re-exploded in order
to inject the current bundle ID.  The re-explosion was failing in a few ways:
1. The in-memory AAR cache was being modified while being iterated over causing
   an exception that aborted the process.
   - This is now fixed by copying the in-memory cache before calling methods
   that can mutate it.
2. The cache used to track which AARs should be exploded was getting out of
   sync with the AARs in the project.
   - The cache is now saved when it's mutated except for in ShouldExplode().
   ShouldExplode() does not rewrite the cache as this can lead to a large
   number of cache rewrites.
3. ShouldExplode() is initially called with a reference to the source AAR file
   then later queried with the target AAR directory (when exploded) causing
   a cache miss when querying the AAR explosion cache and ultimately returning
   the wrong explosion state to the caller since it expected an archive (AAR)
   to interrogate rather than a directory.
   - Since source AAR paths are not available at the time of re-evaluating
   dependencies, the exploded directory can potentially be passed to
   ShouldExplode().  If a directory (from an exploded AAR) is passed to
   ShouldExplode() the source AAR path is derived from the filename and
   looked up in the cache.  If the cache isn't present this falls back to
   assuming the presence of a directory means that the archive really
   should be exploded.

msg:
Added a script that uses Gradle to build a set of dependencies.

This is needed in order to add proguard support within Unity. Unity doesn't
expose their internal android build pipeline to hook in proguard or offer
support for it, and yet on android when linking to so many libraries there's a
major issue with hitting dex limits.

The script handles generating a complete gradle project, with a configurable set
of dependencies. We then build the project using proguard and extract the useful
parts to a folder in an Eclipse / Ant format (which can be used with Unity).

This approach allows us to re-use many of the prerequisite steps and
functionality built into Gradle and the Gradle Android plugin. By triggering the
proguard step, we automatically get resource compilation, dependency resolution,
macro expansion, proguard config aggregation, and other prerequisite,
without replicating the toolchain.

Added support for individual ABIs when using AARs with native libs.

Unity's legacy system includes all ABIs from AARs when targeting
a single ABI.  This results in APK size bloat and also can break
plugins when targeting x86 platforms that support dynamic
recompilation.

This commit adds an Android target ABI poller which triggers
an event when the user changes the ABI in the editor.  If the
ABI changes the resolver is notified and potentially re-processes
the AARs included in the project to strip the native libraries that
are not required by the target ABI.

The behavior varies by Unity version:
* Unity 4:
  - Always unpacks AARs, always targets the FAT ABI.
* Unity 5 (Legacy Build):
  - Unpacks AARs if they contain native libraries and a single ABI
    is selected.
  - Removes ABIs that are not required for the selected build target.
* Unity 5 (Gradle Build):
  - Same as Unity 5 legacy build.  Unity's Gradle integration - similar
    to the legacy build blindly includes unneccesary ABIs.

In addition, this change fixes synchronization of the AAR explode cache.
AARs are now indexed by package name and removed from the cache when
they're stale.

msg:
Workaround for package resolution when using Google Play Services.

The Jar Resolver doesn't evaluate the entire dependency graph when
evaluating dependencies which leads it to choose the latest version of
a package without re-evaluating all constraints associated with the
package.  This poses a problem for Google Play Services dependencies
which all need to be pinned to the same version to function correctly.

Rather than implementing a replacement dependency resolution system -
which could take a while - this patch adds the concept of "version
locking" to pin all packages within a group to a particular version.
This is applied to Google Play Services packages such that a
consistent, compatible version is selected across the package set.

In addition, this patch adds support for verbose logging in the
the PlayServicesSupport component of the Jar Resolver with an
option to enable / disable the functionality.

msg:
Fixed Gradle build when a single target ABI is selected.

Unity's Gradle build does not correctly specify the target ABI.  This
results in shared libraries of all ABIs being incorrectly included in
built APK if raw AARs are included.  In addition, Unity's Gradle build
does not include shared libraries (.so files) in Ant-style projects.

To workaround these problems, this patch explodes (unpacks) AARs that
contain shared libraries or require variable expansion and repacks
them as AARs so they can be included in Gradle builds.

In addition, this patch works around the renamed
UnityEditor.PlayerSettings.bundleIdentifier property.

msg:
Strip square brackets from version values in pom files.

Square brackets in the maven way of saying 'depend on this version
exactly', which JarResolver already tries to accomodate.
Prior to this change, square brackets breaks dependency resolution.

Change-Id: Ief395dfd370f65f8470c87e72c36db268ee2b33c

Restored AAR state cache from AAR files in the project.

The AAR state cache was moved into the Temp directory in change
I5a24cc1916c3cd941f5b1e80c4bf04e58211d1c6.  This results in the cache
being deleted when Unity closes which is problematic as the resolver
uses the cache to avoid touching the local maven repo when
auto-resolution is enabled.  This patch recreates the AAR state cache
when the JarResolver plugin is loaded as no cache file exists.

msg: Merge "Bumped version to 1.2.17 and fixed a typo in JarResolver log statement."

Updated code to avoid deprecated NUnit lib calls.

Unity 5.6+ now ships with NUnit 3.0.  NUnit 3.0 removes a suite of
deprecated methods that we were using in our unit tests
(see https://github.com/nunit/docs/wiki/Breaking-Changes#nunit-30).

This change migrates our unit tests from deprecated method usage to
methods that work with earlier revisions of NUnit and NUnit 3.0+.

Change-Id: Ib6722071087542be0b01288aae6bdb2c90cfe8ae

Added support for the IOSResolver to preserve pods from Unity.

When GVR is enabled Unity creates a Podfile with the GVR sdk, which
we parse and assume all of the pod dependencies in the Podfile we
generate. Also, since this causes the workspace to be loaded, we don't
need to inject dependencies from podfiles into the xcodeproject.

msg: Merge branch 'master' of https://github.com/googlesamples/unity-jar-resolver

Merge pull request #57 from prime31/master

get rid of warning when not on Android using runtime check

Fixed bug which caused version handler managed files to get disabled.

* Version Handler was not re-enabling DLLs when only one version of the
  DLL was present in a project.  This would result in DLLs getting disabled
  when importing multiple plugins with version managed DLLs.
  e.g
  - Import plugin 1, version handler runs and enables MYDLL (which was
    disabled in the .unitypackage metadata)
  - Import plugin 2, version handler would not enable MYDLL (which is
    now disabled due to the .unitypackage metadata)
* Added an option to enable / disable versioned file renaming.  Renaming
  is crazy expensive especially on windows where in some cases this causes
  all DLLs to be reloaded in Unity causing 3-4s delay per DLL.
  It's possible someone relies upon the renaming behavior so it's still
  available as an option in the settings menu.
* Improved Version Handler logging.
* Improved layout of the Version Handler settings dialog.
* Added a more useful warning when Version Handler isn't supported by an
  old version of Unity.

msg:
Force expansion of AARs with native components when using Unity 2017.

In contrast to Unity 5.x, Unity 2017's internal build system does not include
native libraries included in AARs.
Forcing expansion of AARs with native components generates an Ant / Eclipse
project for each AAR which is correctly included by Unity 2017's internal
build system.

msg:
Bootstrap DLL for VersionHandler.

VersionHandler has grown into a component that does more than it was
originally intended.  This has resulted in a lot of revisions that has required
VersionHandler itself to be versioned as it's shared between multiple Unity
plugins.  Since the VersionHandler needs to execute to enable other editor
plugins when it's versioned itself that leads to a compile error on import
when multiple VersionHandler plugins are imported into a project at different
versions.

To resolve this issue, VersionHandler has been split into
Google.VersionHandler.dll and Google.VersionHandlerImpl.dll where
Google.VersionHandler.dll is unversioned and updated infrequently and
Google.VersionHandlerImpl.dll is versioned and potentially updated frequently.
Google.VersionHandler.dll provides the public interface to the module calling
into the implementation using reflection as Google.VersionHandlerImpl.dll
may not be initially loaded at compile time.

msg:
Linux library renaming based upon Unity version.

VersionHandler will now rename Linux libraries so they can target Unity
versions that require different file naming.  Libraries need to be labelled
gvh_linuxlibname-${basename} in order to be considered for renaming.
e.g gvh_linuxlibname-MyLib will be named MyLib.so in Unity 5.5 and below and
libMyLib.so in Unity 5.6 and above.

Also, changed VersionHandlerImpl so that it is only disabled via the command
line option -gvh_disable similar to VersionHandler (bootstrap) this should
reduce confusion when it doesn't run by default in batch mode.

msg:
Added notification on VersionHandler update completion

When the VersionHandler exceutes it sometimes needs to refresh the
asset database in order to compile newly enabled DLLs.  Since asset
database refresh operations are asynchronous it's not easy for an editor
script to determine when compilation is complete.   This commit adds
functionality to the VersionHandler which allows a developer to provide
a list of static methods that are called when an update operation is
complete.  This makes it easier for build scripts to start the build
process for a target platform when the VersionHandler's project
preprocessing operations are complete.

msg:
Improved the reliability of GradlePrebuild.

This change fixes the android build tools and platform
detection to use the android SDK package manager instead
of relying on non-public Unity SDKs. This change also
tries to use a single build-tools version if possible in
order to maintain stability on intermediates generated from
the gradle toolchain.

Change-Id: I669106e5f9e214ee1afb451539a4bc5da9939ed6
Merge "Improved the reliability of GradlePrebuild."

Added support for single ABI stripping when using Gradle Prebuild.

Bug: 62657139

Change-Id: I494b4c23a3ae17c83d7e0a4a68f3182e7623243e

Fixed < Unity 5.6 compatibility broken by UnityCompat addition.

I669106e5f9e214ee1afb451539a4bc5da9939ed6 added a hard dependency
upon the PlayerSettings.Android.minSdkVersion enumeration which
was introduced in Unity 5.6, essentially breaking compatibility which
is the whole point of the UnityCompat module.

Bug: 62657139
Change-Id: I28bf1ccd91c9a6fe526e16f551d0bdf7d6ae3d18

Added support for Gradle based resolution when prebuild is disabled.

This patch deprecates most of PlayServicesSupport.cs now relegating the
module to speeding up the process of determining whether to execute a
resolution step.  In addition, since Gradle is now used to fetch Android
dependencies, non-local artifacts are now supported.

The legacy behavior is still in place and installation of packages via
the Android package manager is retained when using Gradle resolution.

msg:
Apply build settings from Cocoapod xcconfig files.

When Xcode Project Cocoapod integration was enabled the IOS Resolver was not
applying build settings from Cocoapod xcconfig files.  This could result in
disasterous consequences when using a combination of binary and source pods
as binaries may be compiled with different (i.e the default) build settings
where the source pods wouldn't have the appropriate build flags applied.

This patch parses each xcconfig file and injects the build settings into
Unity's generated Xcode project.

In addition, this cleans up an unused variable and makes resource embedding
in the JarResolver DLL consistent across xbuild / msbuild versions.

msg:
Improved Android resolver auto-resolution and Gradle dependency cleanup

When using Gradle to resolve, stale transitive dependencies were not
being cleaned up.  In addition, auto-resolution was not efficient when
using Gradle to build.  This patch introduces a ProjectSettings file
that is used to track the set of dependencies in a project.  When the
set of dependencies declared by *Deps.cs files or the dependencies under
Plugins/Android don't match what is expected, auto resolution is triggered.

Also, fixed the Gradle Prebuild to call the completion delegate.

msg:
Fixed Android Resolution failure with spaces in paths.

Android Resolution would fail if the paths to additional repositories
contained spaces or other characters that need to be escaped in URIs.
This escapes all URIs before running Gradle to download required
artifacts.

Change-Id: I59aa80d1dfc090705d4d843aa8c0912b0e76d8e1

Change-Id: I8a8588bcd0b06777bd5d6c60e5c1b4d0ec460ed2

Fixed compile error when building with the Mono 2.0 toolchain.

The old mono 2.0 compiler does not allow methods with optional arguments
to be passed as delegates unless the delegate matches all required and
optional arguments specified by the method.  This fixes instances where
PlayServicesSupport.Log was being passed as
PlayServicesSupport.LogMessageWithLevel where method signatures differ
by PlayServicesSupport.Log requiring an optional bool argument
(verbose).

Change-Id: I225869e4c7fd43af0dadba067fb49cc68b3540a4

Support for project level settings.

Allows storage of project level settings for all components of the
Play Services Resolver plugin.

* Moved common logging logic into a common module.
* Moved xml utilities module into VersionHandlerImpl so that it can be
  shared by other components.
* Added ProjectSettings class which stores settings with a project and
  allows a user to switch between project vs. application level settings.
  By default all settings are now per-project rather than application wide.
  Application settings are applied where project settings are currently not
  available to enable the transition of user's existing application level
  settings to project level settings.

Changed iOS Resolver to "pod" command via the shell by default.

Some developers customize their shell environment to use custom ssh certs
to access internal git repositories that host pods so executing "pod" via
the shell will work for these scenarios. The drawback of executing "pod"
via the shell could potentially cause users problems if they break their
shell environment.  Though users who customize their shell environments
will be able to resolve these issues.

msg:
Sped up auto-resolution with XML specified dependencies.

The XML dependency parser now limits its' search for XML files to text file
assets.  For large projects this should increase the speed of resolution.

Fixes #70
Change-Id: I633745ce7133abe793ce3f6044c70532523a2a9b

Fixed Android Gradle resolution succeeding when artifacts are missing.

Gradle removes all missing artifacts from the resolved set.  This commit
compares the set of Gradle resolved artifacts with the user specified set
and adds missing artifacts to the list of artifacts to copy.  This results
in missing artifacts being reported correctly by download_artifacts.gradle.

Bug: 66472828
Change-Id: I53c8e31caccad1e7697312960440a65ef5b45a19

Report resolution failures when Android resolution via menu.

Pop-up dialog now displays an error message if Android resolution fails.

Bug: 66472828
Change-Id: Ide0829d1473fa5fbbb6da38352ed98595bbd0e9c

Added conflict resolution for unmanaged Android libraries.

Libraries that are not managed by the Android resolver can conflict with
managed libraries.  These conflicts can result in obscure build errors that
confuse users.  This commit adds logic to find potentially conflicting
libraries and prompt the user to clean up old versions.   Newer versions
of unmanaged libraries will be left to the user to clean up manually.

Bug: 36003647
Change-Id: Ic6af0be40d81faa704161505a7c28fd98c15163f

1.2.53 release.

New Features
* Changed Android Resolver "resolution complete" dialog so that it now displays
  failures.
* Android Resolver now detects conflicting libraries that it does not manage
  warning the user if they're newer than the managed libraries and prompting
  the user to clean them up if they're older or at the same version.

Bug Fixes
* Improved Android Resolver auto-resolution speed.
* Fixed bug in the Gradle Android Resolver which would result in resolution
  succeding when some dependencies are not found.

Fixed Android Resolver reporting non-existent conflicts.

In some cases Unity's asset database can be out of sync with the file system
leading to the asset database reference files that have been deleted.  This
would lead to FindAndResolveConflicts() reporting conflicting dependencies
(AARs / JARs / exploded projects) for non-existent files.

Fixed Version Handler renaming files with underscores.

If the "Rename to Canonical Fileanmes" setting was enabled the
Version Handler would rename files such that everything following
the first underscore is removed.  e.g my_neat_file would be renamed
to my.  This is fixed by checking the value(s) after the field prefix
when parsing metadata from filenames.  e.g _v1.2.3 would indicate a
version number field where _vFOO would not.

msg:
Added support for granular builds of Google Play Services.

Version 15 and above of Google Play Services are no longer shipped
concurrently, each component can now depend upon an arbitrary version.
This change disables version locking of Google Play Services components for
new releases.

To facilitate more complex versioning of Google Play Services and the
possibility of multiple Unity plugins depending upon different versions, this
changes the conflict resolution algorithm to progressively loosen requirements
until a set of non-conflicting packages is found.

To validate this functionality, new integration test data has been added along
with a script to generate new test maven artifacts in future.

Fixed resolution when the Assets/Plugins/Android is named incorrectly.

incorrectly.  For example, `Assets/plugins/Android` is recognized by
Unity as C# filesystem methods like Directory.Exists() are case
insensitive.  However, the Android Resolver uses Gradle to perform
resolution which handles case sensitive filenames.

Fixes issue #110

Fixed mixed version locked package handling in Android Resolver.

* Fixed #127 mixing version-locked & non version-locked Android packages
  during resolution. Version locking is disabled when a package in a set is not
  version-locked.
* Fixed #123 an issue where the specified Android package order would change the
  resolved package version.  When the gradle script is called by the
  Unity plugin this could lead to non-deterministic results given multiple
  references to the same package at different versions.

Improved support for batch mode execution of resolution steps.

* Moved main thread task execution logic to the RunOnMainThread class.
  This simplifies the process of scheduling execution on the main thread in
  the Unity editor and enabled addition of support for synchronous execution
  when running in batch mode where UnityEditor.EditorApplication.update is not
  called.
* CommandLine and CommandLineDialog classes will now execute all command line
  operations synchronously when running in batch mode.
* Added logging to CommandLineDialog in batch mode and when running with
  verbose logging enabled.
* Moved batch mode testing logic and Unity version checking to the
  ExceutionEnvironment class.
* Moved all explicit use of EditorApplication.update to RunOnMainThread methods
  so tasks are executed correctly in batch mode.
* Added batch mode support to CommandLineDialog (Unity crashes when showing
  editor windows in batch mode with no graphics).
* Fixed variable replacement in AndroidManifest.xml files.
  Values like "${applicationId}.foo" were being replaced by simply the
  applicationId variable, stripping the ".foo".

msg:
Fixed recursive polling job execution.

It's possible for a polling job to schedule additional polling tasks.  In batch
mode, since everything runs on the main thread with multiple invocations of
ExecutePollingJobs(), instances of ExecutePollingJobs() up the stack can be in a
state where the job iterator ends up pointing outside of the job list leading to
an OutOfRangeException.

This commit changes ExecutePollingJobs() to stop executing jobs when the end of
the job list is reached.  In addition, this changes PollOnUpdateUntilComplete()
to only poll until the currently scheduled job is complete in batch mode to
prevent waiting for all jobs to finish.

- Release tasks now update the minimal set of files required to generate a

- Integration test tasks have been added that simplifies the process of setting
  up and executing integration tests for editor components.

Initial integration tests have been added for the Version Handler and
Android Resolver that cover:

- Android Resolver dependency resolution for Gradle, non-Gradle and exported
  builds in Unity 5.x and above.

In addition, fixed package manager tests.

msg:
Support plugin builds with Unity Hub installations.

The build script now searches for Unity installations in default Unity Hub
installation directories and uses the first one it finds.

Bug: 80191093
Change-Id: I0451c329374382e3e6bfd6ae1693e33f477e8b7e

1.2.76 release of the Play Services Resolver.

-- Bug Fixes
* Fixed variable replacement in AndroidManifest.xml files in the Android
  Resolver.
  Version 1.2.75 introduced a regression which caused all variable replacement
  to replace the *entire* property value rather than the component of the
  property that referenced a variable.  For example,
  given "applicationId = com.my.app", "${applicationId}.foo" would be
  incorrectly expanded as "com.my.app" rather than "com.my.app.foo".  This
  resulted in numerous issues for Android builds where content provider
  initialization would fail and services may not start.

-- Changed
* Gradle prebuild experimental feature has been removed from the Android
  Resolver.  The feature has been broken for some time and added around 8MB
  to the plugin size.
* Added better support for execution of plugin components in batch mode.
  In batch mode UnityEditor.update is sometimes never called - like when a
  single method is executed - so the new job scheduler will execute all jobs
  synchronously from the main thread.

msg:
Fixed compile warnings in CommandLineDialog.

Change-Id: Iaeea62c99aa2e323602c9b2a83163c6ce8be833c

Enable verbose logging when running in batch mode.

To aid debugging batch execution scenarios, all plugins using the
Google.Logger now have verbose logging enabled in batch mode.

Change-Id: I935b34de7b1757f36f8ad0eaec6dfaa0b3fa365d

Made all version handler dialogs conditional on interactive execution.

In batch mode, all editor dialogs generate a lot of log noise.  This
moves all version handler dialogs behind the batch mode execution flag
so no attempt is made to show them in non-interactive environments.

Change-Id: I1bf270501a87d898e9e94ac22c36e427251bfb28

Cleanup of some duplicate of file deletion logic in the Android Resolver.

Change-Id: Iefa1ea90e9a6b210d21c9f2d471ba276af035cb8

Fixed VersionHandler bootstrapper calling completion multiple times.

The VersionHandler bootstrapper was sometimes calling UpdateCompleteMethods
multiple times.  This commit clears all cached UpdateCompleteMethods after
VersionHandlerImpl has been successfully bootstrapped.

Change-Id: I0f349c73c1ce37003ac52a79f8f48f197537f9b5

Disabled auto-resolution in batch mode.

Auto-resolution of Android assets is pretty much what you never want
as common patterns involve changing build settings before kicking off
a batch mode build and each build setting change kicks off the Android
Resolver.  This disables auto-resolution unless Unity is being executed
interactively.

Change-Id: I554ce114b8c3e8ac761179408d78da4df04ba86d

Cancel all scheduled Android auto-resolution jobs on resolve.

When Android Resolution is invoked explicitly via the Resolve() method
or implicitly via the auto-resolver, state has changed such that all
outstanding auto-resolve jobs are no longer required.  This modifies
the Android Resolver to cancel all scheduled auto-resolve job whenever
any resolve action is scheduled.  If an auto-resolve job is currently
executing it will run to completion before starting the next scheduled
job.

Also, the resolver no longer executes a resolution job if no dependencies
are specified.

Change-Id: I2f6459c9d459e85abdd1152af0da067c52ae2cbe

Only create jar files with a manifest.

When repacking jar / aar files after stripping ABIs or expanding
variables in AndroidManifest.xml files, the JAR tool is used to create
the new archive.  By default JAR will generate a manifest which is
only required for .jar files so this patch disables manifest generation
for all non-jar files being archived by the tool.

Change-Id: Id476701ed70b11f937468026514057a198917b6b

Option to build and package symbols in the plugin.

./gradlew -PDEBUG=1 exportPlugin

will now include .mdb files in the plugin.

Change-Id: Ib17a9ba61ec615bd22c2830a75616b5a46df16a9

Added support for Android ABI filtering in Unity 2018.

* Changed Android ABI selection to support sets of selected ABIs
  introduced in Unity 2018.
* Added tests to validate ABIs are correctly filtered from resolved
  Android artifacts based upon the Unity editor's build settings.
* Reduced build property polling frequency.

Tested: Validated with the integration test using Unity 5.6 and Unity 2018.

msg:
Version 1.2.77 release.

- Changed
* Android Resolver now supports Unity's 2018 ABI filter (i.e arm64-v8a).
* Reduced Android Resolver build option polling frequency.
* Disabled Android Resolver auto-resolution in batch mode.  Users now need
  to explicitly kick off resolution through the API.
* All Android Resolver and Version Handler dialogs are now disabled in batch
  mode.
* Verbose logging for all plugins is now enabled by default in batch mode.
* Version Handler bootstrapper has been improved to no longer call
  UpdateComplete multiple times.  However, since Unity can still reload the
  app domain after plugins have been enabled, users still need to store their
  plugin state to persistent storage to handle reloads.

- Bug Fixes
* Android Resolver no longer incorrectly adds MANIFEST.MF files to AARs.
* Android Resolver auto-resolution jobs are now unscheduled when an explicit
  resolve job is started.

msg:
Improved Android library conflict resolution.

* Refactors download_artifacts.gradle to use Version, VersionRange and
  PackageSpecifier classes.  This made is easier to fix issues with version
  comparisons.
* Added support for alphanumeric version strings.
  Fixes #133
* Fixed issue which caused version locked and non-version locked dependencies
  to be treated as not conflicting.  Fixes #130, fixes #139.
* Fixed conflict resolution when non-existent artifacts are referenced.
  Fixes #130
* Added test cases to cover the above issues.
* Fixed latest version of duplicate packages not being selected.
  Fixes #130

Bug: 112656012

Change-Id: I5f9b51b2b8533d1f0d3f4e6799be9adf777b1a35

Attempted fix for race when reading / writing explode cache.

The Android Resolver uses a temporary file to cache information about AARs /
JARs that can be preserved across recompilation which forces DLL reloads.
Methods used to read / write the cache were not in using statements which could
result in file handles being left open after they're read written.  In addition,
if a file operation failed for this optimization, the Android Resolver would
fail to load or stop working.

This wraps file operations in using statements so file handles are closed when
the read / write completes and wraps the file read / write operations in
exception handling so that the resolver doesn't completely fail when accessing
the cache.

Fixes #141

msg:
Fixed transitive dependency selection of version locked packages

Assuming all packages in the group "foo" should be locked to the same version.
And the "foo" group contains:
foo:bar:1.2.3 --> foo:common:1.2.3
foo:bar:1.5.0 --> foo:new-common:1.5.0
foo:baz:1.5.0 --> foo:new-common:1.5.0

If the Android Resolver was configured to download "foo:bar:1.2.3" and
"foo:baz:1.5.0" it would initially resolve all transitive dependencies
of both artifacts then lock them to the same version i.e the following
packages would be pulled and upgraded...

foo:bar:1.2.3 --> foo:bar:1.5.0
foo:common:1.2.3 --> foo:common:1.5.0 (non-existant package!)
foo:bar:1.5.0 --> foo:bar:1.5.0
foo:new-common:1.5.0 --> foo:new-common:1.5.0

foo:common:1.5.0 would be included in the set even though it was removed
from the dependencies of foo:bar in version 1.5.0.

This patch changes the resolver such that version locking is applied to
the first version locked package encountered on each branch of the dependency
tree, typically avoiding the issue of selecting non-existant versions of
packages.  It is still possible that a package in the tree could be removed at
a newer version and will require manual intervention by the user but this
handles common cases.

Fixes #130

msg:
Fixed Android Resolution when the build target isn't Android.

If the Android build target is selected in the Unity editor then
the user selects a different target using the build selection dialog
and then runs the Android resolution process, the wrong applicationId
is retrieved in Unity 5.6 and above and patched into AARs.

This fixes the issue by explicitly retriving the applicationId of the
Android build target rather than the target the user has selected in
the editor.

Change-Id: I0fe93165f3496bffd362476d323ec2fd1c83c27d

Added support for PODS_TARGET_SRCROOT in source Cocoapods.

This commit adds  Xcode project integration support for the PODS_TARGET_SRCROOT
variable. When Cocoapods generates projects the PODS_TARGET_SRCROOT is set for
each Pod's xcproject. Since Xcode project integration merges all Cocoapod build
targets into a single project, this expands the PODS_TARGET_SRCROOT variable
based upon the xcconfig file referencing the variable.  For example...

foo.xcconfig would be generated for the "foo" pod, so this expands
PODS_TARGET_SRCROOT as "${PODS_ROOT}/foo" to emulate the variable reference
in a Cocoapods xcproject.

msg:
Fix ScheduleAutoResolve() triggering AutoResolve() twice.

ScheduleAutoResolve() will schedule an AutoResolve() via a the lambda
for the function RunOnMainThread.PollOnUpdateUntilComplete(). The
lambda can potentially be called again after AutoResolve() has
completed the resolve, resulting in another auto-resolution occuring.

Fixed by checking the autoResolveJobId that is created when scheduling
the AutoResolve(). If autoResolveJobId is 0 then we can assume the
resolution has been scheduled and we do not call AutoResolve() again.

Bug: 118340254
Change-Id: Ia62a298f71aa96e835602669859f33a767cc1a3c

msg: Fix minor typo in android resolver log

Merge pull request #161 from vitorbaraujo/fix-log-typo

Fixed incorrect dates in changelog.

Merge pull request #162 from Si1ver/master

Added ability to specify 'path' in iOS dependency xml to allow for development pods

Moved repacking of AARs into a temporary directory.

The AAR repacking logic would apply transformations to files in the Unity
project's Assets directory.  This has become an issue as Unity 2018 now
creates .meta files for each file added in the Assets directory.  These
.meta files end up being repacked into AARs which are rejected by the latest
Android Studio gradle plugin.

This moves AAR repacking into a temporary directory, when all file
transformations are complete the result is moved under the Unity project's
Assets directory.

Fixes #169
Bug: 120034219
Change-Id: Ib9bd23a8e34ddf8cfde7c8a31291a5e6460c1bdd

Fixed Version Handler failing to rename some files.

On Windows, Version Handler would attempt to rename files to the same
path due to mismatched directory separators of source and target paths.
This would result in errors being reported in some plugins (e.g Firebase)
that would warn users about not being able to rename file like
"Unable to rename a/b/c.so to a\b\c.so" as they point at same file.

Fixes #159

Only perform auto-resolution on the first scene while building.

The Android Resolver was running the resolution process for every
scene included in a build which could significantly extend build times.
Even worse, OnPostProcessScene is called when starting the player in the
editor which would slow down player startup times.

This changes the synchronous resolution process to only run if a build
is in progress and also ensures resolution only run for the first scene
in the project.

Fixes #170

Fixed parsing of version ranges containing whitespace.

Version ranges containing whitespace e.g "[1.2.3, 4.5.6]" were not
being parsed correctly, leading to the Android Resolver failing
to resolve dependencies correctly when users added whitespace to
version ranges.

Fixes #164

msg:
Disabled build system change polling when auto-resolution is disabled.

Methods that used to be hooked into the editor update tick are now able to be
unhooked and will not automatically be assigned via the PlayServicesResolver's
static constructor if auto resoltution is turned off in the settings.

Original: https://github.com/googlesamples/unity-jar-resolver/pull/173
Change-Id: I91f5019f2dec77f9470f38ac8c9fb978a022d7a6

Reduce memory allocation caused by VersionHandler.FindClass().

VersionHandler.FindClass() is called a lot throughout the plugin so this
commit changes the method to memoize the result of each query to remove
any allocation from future searches for the same class.

Some searches would allocate ~500kb, this eliminates this allocation
entirely.

Issue #146
Bug: 121162585

Change-Id: I28c3ddcdce8d2c9645677ca6bbd11acdaa2ed626

Reduced Android Resolver property polling frequency.

Even though PropertyPoller had a checkIntervalInSeconds property, the
Poll() method required the current value of the property which ended up
polling the propety *every* frame rather than every checkIntervalInSeconds.
This changes the Poll() method to accept a delegate that retrieves the
current value instead of requiring the value on every call to the method.

msg:
Merge remote-tracking branch 'origin/master' into merging

Change-Id: Ib6fa9e9c59f433d1800bd28196a553e25a605fc9

Merge pull request #179 from Si1ver/master

Fixed typos in documentation and comments.

Changed some file operations to workaround Windows permission issues.

The Android Resolver processes AARs and JARs in temporary directories
moving the results to the Unity project when it's complete.

Some users (e.g firebase/quickstart-unity#295 ) have reported that
moving files or directories from the temporary folder can result in
exceptions due to lack of permissions.

I've been unable to reproduce the user's issue. However, some sources
on the web suggest that old .NET versions of File.Move() and
Directory.Move() do not correctly propagage permissions on Windows.

To workaround broken implementations of File.Move() and Directory.Move()
on Windows this patch does the following:
* Moves all temporary files under the Unity project's Temp directory
  instead of the system temporary folder.  This folder should be writable
  by the user otherwise basic operations in Unity would fail.
* Changes File.Move() and Directory.Move() operations to copy and delete
  on Windows so that permissions of files and folders in the target location
  inherit from the Unity project folder.

In addition, this modifies ProcessAar() to log an error but continue when an
error occurs so that a modal progress bar isn't left displayed for the Unity
session.

Change-Id: Ib55ef90d2b8418fb262ea50756600f438a0b91a6
GitHub: firebase/quickstart-unity/issues/295

msg:
Revise the way Xcode Project Integration works, in order to let cocoapods do more of the heavy lifting.

Basically, just add the Pods project to the Unity-iPhone project as a "subproject" (the way you used to do multiproject builds before workspaces), and add it to the build of the main target.  Also, don't suppress the pod command's normal project integration (i.e., don't add the line "install! 'cocoapods', :integrate_targets => false" to the Podfile) since that step does all of the work in setting up the build dependencies between the Unity-iPhone project and the Pods project.  That includes propagating build settings (search paths, flags, etc) from the pods into the main project.  (I believe this means the "bitcodeEnabled" attribute is now superfluous, but I didn't disturb the implementation of it for backwards compatibility.)

This change, aside from simplifying the code quite a bit, also lifts some restrictions that the old implementation had.  Local (i.e., "Development") pods that are located outside the Pods subdirectory are now supported.  Also, the resources in source pods are properly included in the app build.

Also leveraged some static calls provided by Unity's PBXProject class for finding the path project and main target name, so that logic is no longer needed in this code.

Feedback:

Revert some stuff needed by precompiled DLLs and certain plugins.  Also use an older overload of PBXProject.AddFile() for backwards compatibility with older versions of PBXProject.

msg:
Add support for VersionHandler to enable/disable files based on build target by renaming them.

Currently, we disable certain files per-platform by using PluginHandler, but this only works for libraries (.dll and the like), and does not work on some earlier versions of unity.  This change adds the ability for VersionHandler to disable files by modifying their file extension (from .zzz -> .zzz_DISABLED) based on the platform being targeted - using the same Asset Labels already being used for PluginHandler files.

Removed use of EditorUtility.DisplayProgressBar in Android Resolver

EditorUtility.DisplayProgressBar() is very flakey, it can end up in odd
states where it can never be cleared.

This removes the use of EditorUtility.DisplayProgressBar from the Android
Resolver, instead moving the progress bar display to the CommandLineDialog.
In addition, long running operations like labeling assets, have been made
asynchronous by scheduling each iteration on the main thread.

Finally, this leaves the Android Resolver window open if resolution fails,
results in one or more warnings or verbose logging is enabled so that it's
easier to inspect the failure logs.

Gracefully handle exceptions on file deletion.

Some users are seeing exceptions when the Android Resolver creates and

Fixed compile error with old C# compilers.

Change-Id: I2205a22a6f8a9a3d689716d307bcc72eceeb71bc

Fixed up maven repos embedded in Unity projects when in Gradle builds.

When resolving Android dependencies using Gradle and a mainTemplate.gradle
file, srcaar artifacts in maven repos embedded in the Unity project are
renamed to aar so they can be included in the Android build process.

However, some plugins (like Google Play Games) ship with Maven POMs that
refrence the srcaar artifacts directly rather than the aar artifacts.
This results in the renamed aar files being ignored in the Android build
process.

This commit patches Maven POMs so they reference the correct artifact
when the packaging is changed by the Gradle Android Resolution step.
If libraries are removed, the POMs are updated to point at the packaging
for the artifact in the directory (e.g srcaar).

Fixes #208

msg:
Version 1.2.112

* Android Resolver: Added option to disable addition of dependencies to
  mainTemplate.gradle.
  See `Assets > Play Services Resolver > Android Resolver > Settings`.
* Android Resolver: Made paths to local maven repositories in
  mainTemplate.gradle relative to the Unity project when a project is not
  being exported.
* Android Resolver: Fixed builds with mainTemplate.gradle integration in
  Unity 2019.
* Android Resolver: Changed dependency inclusion in mainTemplate.gradle to
  use "implementation" or "compile" depending upon the version of Gradle
  included with Unity.
* Android Resolver: Gracefully handled exceptions if the console encoding
  can't be modified.
* Android Resolver: Now gracefully fails if the AndroidPlayer directory
  can't be found.

Change-Id: Ib9db961c1b41eddf817b9e1827da9206c01ca6ef

Adding VersionHandler support for multiple Target, DotNet labels.

Change-Id: I39ff0409059c3970283c9541088b4e42464bdead
Merge "Adding VersionHandler support for multiple Target, DotNet labels."

Added compatible way to get the AndroidPlayer directory.

BuildPipeline.GetPlaybackEngineDirectory() was added in Unity 2019
to get the playback engine directory.  The Android playback engine
directory is required to determine the version of Gradle shipped
with the plugin so this does not work in Unity < 2019.

This patch adds a compatible but slower way to retrieve the
AndroidPlayer directory which also fixes the generation of Gradle
dependency inclusion statements in Unity < 2019

Fixes #213
Bug: 133243196
Change-Id: I455ec6de28900a31ea414bd1ff657404e611b0fb

More gracefully handle Maven repos being moved in a project.

Some developers move plugins around in the project breaking local
maven repo paths.  This commit falls back to searching for local
maven repos if the directory isn't found, warning the user of the
file referencing the broken directory link along with the new
path.

Bug: 112525947
Change-Id: Ibfc2bc231904ccf93919edd9b5c78d0814e3d28b

Version 1.2.113

* Android Resolver: If local repos are moved, the plugin will search the
  project for matching directories in an attempt to correct the error.
* Version Handler: Files can be now targeted to multiple build targets
  using multiple "gvh_" asset labels.
* Android Resolver: "implementation" or "compile" are now added correctly
  to mainTemplate.gradle in Unity versions prior to 2019.

msg:
Only poll build properties for auto-resolution with Android build target.

Unity 2019.x throws an exception when
BuildPipeline.GetPlaybackEngineDirectory() is called and the Android player
isn't installed.  The Android build target can't be selected if it's not
installed, so we shouldn't be polling the build system if the build target
isn't Android.  This patch disables build system property polling on assembly
load if the build target isn't Android.

Bug: 134665717

including the missing directory name in the message.

Fixed resolution of Android dependencies without version specifiers.

Android Resolver's artifact downloader script was failing if a
dependency in the graph did not specify a version for an artifact.
This commit makes it possible to handle empty version specifications
in dependencies.

In addition, this adds more information to conflicting package log
messages and eliminates the creation of copy tasks for output
files that already exist.

msg:
Worked around bug in Gradle 5.1.x

Gradle now runs task execution in parallel by default but due to
https://github.com/gradle/gradle/issues/6068 it's not possible
to capture stdout / stderr from individual tasks which breaks
download_artifacts_test.gradle.  This commit modifies the test to run
all tasks serially, prepares for the Gradle bug to be fixed and
cleans up the output a little when tests fail.

https://github.com/googlesamples/unity-jar-resolver/issues/145

Change-Id: Ifee400beaa4544b3d9145cce51b69125ffc1f5b9

Update the Gradle wrapper to 5.1.1

This is required to use Kotlin plugins like the Jetifier with
Gradle's embedded Kotlin runtime.

Bug: 113575309
Change-Id: I4d11d30d7944fb95a2c1c2f19f0762d55eda0024

Added Jetifier to download_artifacts.gradle

Added Jetifier support to the Gradle artifact downloader script.
download_artifacts.gradle can now substitute direct and transitive
dependencies on the legacy support libraries to Jetpack and rewrite
references to the legacy support libraries in all downloaded libraries.

This adds unit and integration tests for this functionality but does not
yet connect this to the Android Resolver Unity plugin.

msg:
Do not update asset GUIDs unless the target filename changes.

Developers tend to move the plugin around in their project. However,
the Google.VersionHandler.dll asset GUID was changing with each release
resulting in the DLL failing to load if multiple versions are present in
the project. This patch fixes this issue by only generating new GUIDs
for files that are renamed in the plugin.

msg:
Run Android auto-resolver when relevant settings change.

Auto-resolution was previously relying upon polling for differences in
runtime state which could break if the DLL was reloaded after settings
are changed.  This commit stores the resolution settings with the rest
of the state from the last resolution so that it's possible to
auto-resolve if any of this state changes or the settings change that
require resolution.

msg:
Version 1.2.118

* Android Resolver: Added initial
  [Jetifier](https://developer.android.com/studio/command-line/jetifier)
  integration which simplifies
  [migration](ttps://developer.android.com/jetpack/androidx/migrate)
  to Jetpack ([AndroidX](https://developer.android.com/jetpack/androidx))
  libraries in cases where all dependencies are managed by the Android
  Resolver.
  This can be enabled via the `Use Jetifier` option in the
  `Assets > Play Services Resolver > Android Resolver > Settings` menu.
  Caveats:
  - If your project contains legacy Android Support Library .jar and .aar
    files, these files will need to be removed and replaced with references to
    artifacts on Maven via `*Dependencies.xml` files so that the Jetifier
    can map them to Jetpack (AndroidX) libraries.
    For example, remove the file `support-v4-27.0.2.jar` and replace it with
    `<androidPackage spec="com.android.support:support-v4:27.0.2"/>` in a
    `*Dependencies.xml` file.
  - If your project contains .jar or .aar files that use the legacy Android
    Support Libraries, these will need to be moved into a local Maven repo
    [See this guide](https://maven.apache.org/guides/mini/guide-3rd-party-jars-local.html)
    and then these files should be removed from your Unity project and instead
    referenced via `*Dependencies.xml` files so that the Jetifier can
    patch them to reference the Jetpack lirbaries.

Fixed the Android resolution always running in Unity 2019+

When Unity Hub manages the Android SDK installation, Unity's Android editor
plugin does not return the managed SDK path when the Android Resolver
DLL is loaded.  Instead, the Unity's Android editor plugin will return the
managed SDK path after the first editor update.

Since the static initialization order is non-determinstic, this changes all
property polling in the Android Resolver to defer fetching the initial value
of properties until the first execution of EditorApplication.update.

Fixed line splitting in text area windows.

Unity's labels can only display a limit number of characters so the
text area window splits text into multiple label elements.  The splitting
was not taking into account line breaks so text would be split at very
odd boundaries making things harder to read.  This changes the line
splitting to preferably occur on line breaks.

msg:
Script that generates maven packages for a set of local files.

file_to_maven_package.gradle will create a local Maven repository
for packages that are not found in a set of remote Maven repositories
(currently Maven Central and Google Maven). Packages that are found
in the remote repositories are simply printed to the standard output.

Over half of the implementation is an indexer for Google Maven that
incrementally indexes the repository and stores the index in a local
JSON file. A cache of the index will eventually be hosted on github
and updated periodically to speed up the process of indexing the
repository.

The script exposes the top level tasks:
* install: Creates a local maven repo of supplied input libraries
  and looks for libraries in remote repos printing the results to
  the standard output.
* updateGoogleMavenIndex: Intended to be used from the resolver's
  build script to update the cached index on github.
* searchMavenIndexes: Searches indexed repositories for local
  artifacts by SHA-1 printing the matches to the standard output.

For example:

./gradlew \
  -b source/PlayServicesResolver/scripts/file_to_maven_package.gradle \
  -PTARGET_DIR=$(pwd)/tmp \
  -PGOOGLE_MAVEN_INDEX_URI=file://$(pwd)/unity-jar-resolver/index.zip \
  -PFILE_TO_MAVEN_PACKAGE="\
~/Downloads/flatbuffers-java-1.11.1.jar@\
com.google.flatbuffers:flatbuffers-java:0.0.0;\
source/PlayServicesResolver/scripts/download_artifacts_test_assets/\
m2repository/com/android/support/support-annotations/24.0.0/\
support-annotations-24.0.0.jar@\
com.android.support:support-annotations:24.0.0;\
source/PlayServicesResolver/scripts/download_artifacts_test_assets/\
m2repository/androidx/cursoradapter/cursoradapter/1.0.0/\
cursoradapter-1.0.0.aar@;\
source/PlayServicesResolver/scripts/download_artifacts_test_assets/\
m2repository/com/google/firebase/firebase-app-unity/4.3.0/\
firebase-app-unity-4.3.0.srcaar@" \
   install

Will read the cached Google Maven index file index.zip and incrementally
update it, create a local maven repo under "tmp" and print the following
output...

Packages:
org.psr:com.google.firebase.firebase-app-unity.4.3.0:0.0.0 file:/XXXX/unity-jar-resolver/tmp/
androidx.cursoradapter:cursoradapter:1.0.0 https://dl.google.com/dl/android/maven2/
com.android.support:support-annotations:24.0.0 https://dl.google.com/dl/android/maven2/
com.google.flatbuffers:flatbuffers-java:1.11.1 https://repo.maven.apache.org/maven2/

msg:
Remove AAR cache from GradleResolver

The GradleResolver component maintained an AAR cache which determined the
state of each resolved library and what had changed since the last
resolution.  However, as of 76e7a4434801e277d09248d469e7130409e35c61
whether to run resolution again changed to simply be a function of
whether the specified dependencies, settings or expected output
files changed.  This left the AAR cache in a state where the only value it
added was reducing the number of times a library needed to be inspected
between each resolve step.

This patch merges AAR explosion / patching with inspection to speed up
the AAR processing process which eliminates the gains of the AAR cache.
In cases of incremental resolution, the AAR would be faster but in practice
those cases are pretty rare typically only happening when a plugin in upgraded.

msg:
Fixed execution of methods with interface args using reflection.

GetType() returns the concrete type of an object which caused
InvokeMethod() and InvokeStaticMethod() to not match methods that
take arguments that require interface arguments.

This changes the type check of arguments, to handle overloaded
methods, to check whether an argument is assignable given an argument
which checks for compatibility with the expected interface.

msg:
Only target UnityFramework when integrating Cocoapods.

Unity 2019.3 split iOS builds into a launcher target called
Unity-iPhone and a framework called UnityFramework.

When support for this was added in
I2236b4cfa08f64feb6e6a7957d71987cdacaa6a9 and
I1f236eaeca28bcfd051cc6ea317e5a888efe231e
the iOS resolver was changed to add Cocoapods to both targets.
However, this can result in build errors where symbols are
duplicated from Cocoapods being included in both targets as
UnityFramework is eventually included by Unity-iPhone.

This changes the resolver to only add to the UnityFramework
target when multiple Xcode targets are exported by Unity.

Fixes #282

Slightly improve performance of class lookup in VersionHandler

after the class being searched for was found. This fixes the method to
stop searching when the class has been found.

Synchronized iOS Resolver log level at load time.

This changes the IOSResolver class to set the Logger level when the
class is constructed rather than when the first message is logged.
This also ensures that all changes in log level are propagated to the
underlying Logger instance when the IOSResolver.Log() method isn't used.

Change-Id: Iba31660413ef916351fcddff7ac2d303e43ca4b3

WebRequest class that works in Unity 5.x and 5.5+.

Unity's HTTP API changed from the WWW class in Unity 4.x and
<= 5.5 to the UnityWebRequest class in version 5.5 and beyond.
This commit adds PortableWebRequest which uses reflection to
select the appropriate Unity HTTP request class based upon
runtime availability.

To validate PortableWebRequest, webrequest_launcher.py implements
a local python webserver which echos HTTP requests to the client
allowing the integration test, TestPortableWebRequest.cs, to
validate PortableWebRequest works with GET and PUT requests in
different Unity versions.  Unity versions can be swapped by setting
the UNITY_DIR variable in gradle.properties and running the test
target testVersionHandlerWebRequest.

The integration test file is disabled by default
(i.e named TestPortableWebRequest.cs_DISABLED) as the classes used
by the test aren't available until the Version Handler has
bootstrapped itself. This results in:
- VersionHandler DLL loads
- VersionHandler DLL bootstraps VersionHandlerImpl
- VersionHandlerImpl loads, enables TestPortableWebRequest.cs by
  renaming the file.
- Unity compiles TestPortableWebRequest.cs and starts executing the
  integration test.

The Python environment for the integration test is bootstrapped in
build.gradle using the com.jetbrains.python.envs plugin.
webrequest_launcher.py launches the webserver and, once it's serving,
launches Unity with the PortableWebRequest integration test, when the
test process exits the web server is shut down and the result code is
returned to the Gradle build task.

msg:
Synchronized Version Handler log level at load time.

This changes the VersionHandlerImpl class to set the Logger level when the
class is constructed rather than when the first message is logged.
This also ensures that all changes in log level are propagated to the
underlying Logger instance when the VersionHandlerImpl.Log() method isn't used.

msg:
Documented Gradle vs. mainTemplate.gradle resolution strategies.

The behavior of the Android Resolver is a little opaque, especially
with respect to the mainTemplate.gradle patcher.  This update documents
both the default resolution strategy and the behavior when
mainTemplate.gradle patching is used.

Change-Id: I35ec75faac9390e3923ea2466db188812cf2858f

Fixed Gradle template resolution on Windows.

DIR_UNITYPROJECT is expanded as a path with "\\" directory
separators on Windows which breaks Groovy string escaping when
used in a build.gradle file. This changes the expansion of
DIR_UNITYPROJECT to use a raw string and replace "\\" separators
with POSIX "/" so the path can be used in a file URI.

msg:
Fixed reset of settings if a setting set occurs before a get.

Setting a project setting would change the in-memory settings and then
save the current state to disk which would delete all previously saved
settings.  This changes the ProjectSettings to always load settings
before mutating and saving them.

In addition, this changes VersionHandlerImpl so that running in batch
mode doesn't change the verbose logging setting.

Fixes #301
